00:39:39,000 --> 00:39:42,932
I was proud of my military service.

771
00:39:43,032 --> 00:39:45,266
And I wanted to say,
"You know, I don't think

772
00:39:45,365 --> 00:39:48,065
you guys know that much,"
the American military.

773
00:39:48,166 --> 00:39:51,166
"You know, I think you should think again

774
00:39:51,266 --> 00:39:52,632
"about this enterprise.

775
00:39:52,733 --> 00:39:55,099
And here you go, pal."

776
00:39:55,199 --> 00:39:56,965
Tim Bagwell from Sacramento, California,

777
00:39:57,065 --> 00:39:59,965
still on active duty, and
I say get the hell out.

778
00:40:00,065 --> 00:40:01,065
(cheering)

779
00:40:01,132 --> 00:40:03,766
("Gimme Shelter" continues)

780
00:40:13,333 --> 00:40:15,699
MUSGRAVE: When we threw our medals away,

781
00:40:15,800 --> 00:40:17,300
that got their attention,

782
00:40:17,400 --> 00:40:19,965
because America values those things.

783
00:40:20,065 --> 00:40:21,400
So do we.

784
00:40:21,500 --> 00:40:23,699
That's why it was so important.

785
00:40:23,800 --> 00:40:26,833
NARRATOR: The police had
been ordered not to arrest

786
00:40:26,932 --> 00:40:29,432
any of the veterans, because,

787
00:40:29,532 --> 00:40:32,032
Pat Buchanan, a White House aide, wrote,

788
00:40:32,132 --> 00:40:35,500
they were "being received in a
far more sympathetic fashion

789
00:40:35,599 --> 00:40:37,699
"than other demonstrators.

790
00:40:37,800 --> 00:40:41,432
The 'crazies' will be in town
soon enough," he continued,

791
00:40:41,532 --> 00:40:43,599
"and if we want a confrontation,

792
00:40:43,699 --> 00:40:45,666
let's have it with them."

793
00:40:45,766 --> 00:40:48,065
He was right.

794
00:40:48,166 --> 00:40:50,400
In the days immediately following

795
00:40:50,500 --> 00:40:51,865
the veterans' protest,

796
00:40:51,965 --> 00:40:54,000
other groups of antiwar activists

797
00:40:54,099 --> 00:40:57,099
moved into the capital.

798
00:40:57,199 --> 00:41:00,865
The most radical called
itself the May Day Tribe

799
00:41:00,965 --> 00:41:03,932
and threatened to close the city down.

800
00:41:04,032 --> 00:41:07,266
For three days, they
staged hit-and-run raids

801
00:41:07,365 --> 00:41:09,132
throughout Washington...

802
00:41:09,233 --> 00:41:11,666
blocking bridges and traffic circles,

803
00:41:11,766 --> 00:41:13,099
smashing windows,

804
00:41:13,199 --> 00:41:15,599
hurling rocks, burning cars.

805
00:41:15,699 --> 00:41:16,699
(sirens wailing)

806
00:41:16,766 --> 00:41:18,142
RENNIE DAVIS: If Richard Nixon thought

807
00:41:18,166 --> 00:41:21,465
that this week was something,
wait until the next round.

808
00:41:21,565 --> 00:41:24,132
This is only a warm-up of
what is going to come.

809
00:41:24,233 --> 00:41:26,965
This is going to continue
until the war ends.

810
00:41:27,065 --> 00:41:29,266
NARRATOR: Some 12,000 were arrested...

811
00:41:29,365 --> 00:41:31,833
7,000 on a single day,

812
00:41:31,932 --> 00:41:35,400
the largest number of arrests in 24 hours

813
00:41:35,500 --> 00:41:37,900
in United States history.

814
00:41:38,000 --> 00:41:41,365
BILL ZIMMERMAN: I realized,
coming away from Washington,

815
00:41:41,465 --> 00:41:43,766
that our whole strategy was wrong

816
00:41:43,865 --> 00:41:47,500
and that we were becoming
more and more militant

817
00:41:47,599 --> 00:41:50,365
at a time when more and more Americans

818
00:41:50,465 --> 00:41:51,965
were opposing the war

819
00:41:52,065 --> 00:41:54,565
but were turned off by our militancy.

820
00:41:54,666 --> 00:41:57,565
So we were doing exactly the wrong thing.

821
00:41:57,666 --> 00:42:01,132
NARRATOR: The White House
was initially pleased.

822
00:42:01,233 --> 00:42:04,300
Public sympathy for the
veterans was largely forgotten

823
00:42:04,400 --> 00:42:08,333
in the face of days of
battle in the streets.

824
00:42:08,432 --> 00:42:11,465
Polls showed that most Americans approved

825
00:42:11,565 --> 00:42:13,365
of the arrests.

826
00:42:17,532 --> 00:42:20,565
But those same polls also showed

827
00:42:20,666 --> 00:42:23,365
that most Americans no longer believed

828
00:42:23,465 --> 00:42:27,166
they were being told the
truth about Vietnam.

829
00:42:32,132 --> 00:42:34,833
MUSGRAVE: When I got home, my...
so my dad's pissed off.

830
00:42:34,932 --> 00:42:38,666
'Cause he's-he's a true believer, you know?

831
00:42:40,199 --> 00:42:42,432
He was already receiving threats

832
00:42:42,532 --> 00:42:45,666
because I'd thrown away their medals.

833
00:42:47,432 --> 00:42:50,400
And that pissed my dad off then.

834
00:42:50,500 --> 00:42:53,132
And you would've thought I
hadn't done anything wrong.

835
00:42:53,233 --> 00:42:56,266
Because then somebody outside
the family was messing with me.

836
00:42:56,365 --> 00:42:58,400
And he said, "Son, don't worry.

837
00:42:58,500 --> 00:43:00,400
"Those were your medals. You paid for 'em.

838
00:43:00,500 --> 00:43:01,876
"You can do anything you want with 'em.

839
00:43:01,900 --> 00:43:03,965
"They want to jack with
us, they'll face us both.

840
00:43:04,065 --> 00:43:05,705
We'll-we'll take 'em on in the driveway."

841
00:43:05,800 --> 00:43:08,465
You know? "Yo, Dad."

842
00:43:09,733 --> 00:43:11,666
(applause)

843
00:43:13,365 --> 00:43:15,800
(band playing "Thank
Heaven for Little Girls")

844
00:43:15,900 --> 00:43:18,800
NARRATOR: On June 12, 1971,

845
00:43:18,900 --> 00:43:21,132
Richard Nixon's daughter, Tricia,

846
00:43:21,233 --> 00:43:25,766
married Edward Cox in the
White House Rose Garden.

847
00:43:25,865 --> 00:43:29,465
The country watched it all on television.

848
00:43:32,900 --> 00:43:36,065
The wedding was still news the next day.

849
00:43:36,166 --> 00:43:39,666
But another story on the front
page of theNew York Times

850
00:43:39,766 --> 00:43:42,565
caught the president's attention.

851
00:43:42,666 --> 00:43:45,733
The article, by Neil Sheehan,

852
00:43:45,833 --> 00:43:48,532
was the first report of
what came to be called

853
00:43:48,632 --> 00:43:50,400
the Pentagon Papers,

854
00:43:50,500 --> 00:43:54,065
7,000 pages of highly classified documents

855
00:43:54,166 --> 00:43:56,132
and historical narrative,

856
00:43:56,233 --> 00:43:58,465
compiled secretly at the orders

857
00:43:58,565 --> 00:44:02,333
of former Secretary of
Defense Robert McNamara.

858
00:44:02,432 --> 00:44:05,666
He had hoped a study of the
decision-making process

859
00:44:05,766 --> 00:44:09,266
that had led the United States
to become so deeply involved

860
00:44:09,365 --> 00:44:12,599
in Vietnam would help future policymakers

861
00:44:12,699 --> 00:44:15,300
avoid similar errors.

862
00:44:16,900 --> 00:44:18,932
SHEEHAN: I thought I knew a great deal.

863
00:44:19,032 --> 00:44:21,065
I thought I knew most of
what was worth knowing

864
00:44:21,166 --> 00:44:22,400
about the war.

865
00:44:22,500 --> 00:44:26,199
And, suddenly, I didn't.

866
00:44:26,300 --> 00:44:29,266
It wasn't a reporter's version of an event.

867
00:44:29,365 --> 00:44:31,199
It wasthe ir version of an event.

868
00:44:31,300 --> 00:44:33,532
It was their telegrams, their orders,

869
00:44:33,632 --> 00:44:35,465
their memoranda, et cetera.

870
00:44:49,932 --> 00:44:53,000
NARRATOR: The documents proved
that American presidents

871
00:44:53,099 --> 00:44:54,932
and their closest advisors

872
00:44:55,032 --> 00:44:57,000
had steered the United States

873
00:44:57,099 --> 00:44:59,800
toward deeper involvement in Vietnam,

874
00:44:59,900 --> 00:45:04,300
despite their own grave doubts
about the chances for victory.

875
00:45:13,166 --> 00:45:15,666
They had known that the Saigon government

876
00:45:15,766 --> 00:45:18,166
was weak and incompetent...

877
00:45:25,532 --> 00:45:29,465
...that the enemy was
disciplined and resilient...

878
00:45:35,565 --> 00:45:39,333
...and that the bombing of
the North wasn't working.

879
00:45:46,900 --> 00:45:50,965
Yet, they had routinely
lied about all these things

880
00:45:51,065 --> 00:45:53,599
to Congress and the American people.

881
00:46:17,766 --> 00:46:19,432
(sighs)

882
00:46:19,532 --> 00:46:22,465
I certainly don't endorse

883
00:46:22,565 --> 00:46:27,465
anyone releasing top-secret
material to the press.

884
00:46:29,166 --> 00:46:33,065
Um, on the other hand, uh...

885
00:46:33,166 --> 00:46:36,300
I was very concerned

886
00:46:36,400 --> 00:46:38,833
about the fact that the, uh,

887
00:46:38,932 --> 00:46:44,199
government was not being up
front with the American people

888
00:46:44,300 --> 00:46:47,965
in certain respects with the Vietnam War.

889
00:46:48,065 --> 00:46:51,233
NARRATOR: Two copies of the
report had been stored

890
00:46:51,333 --> 00:46:54,666
at the RAND Corporation,
a California think tank,

891
00:46:54,766 --> 00:46:56,733
where Daniel Ellsberg,

892
00:46:56,833 --> 00:47:01,532
one of the study's 36 authors,
worked as an analyst.

893
00:47:01,632 --> 00:47:04,565
Ellsberg had once supported the war.

894
00:47:04,666 --> 00:47:06,565
He'd served in the Pentagon,

895
00:47:06,666 --> 00:47:09,065
and spent two years working
for the State Department

896
00:47:09,166 --> 00:47:11,300
in Vietnam.

897
00:47:11,400 --> 00:47:15,800
But he had come to see the
war as profoundly immoral,

898
00:47:15,900 --> 00:47:18,400
and hoped that if Americans understood

899
00:47:18,500 --> 00:47:22,833
how administration after
administration had misled them

900
00:47:22,932 --> 00:47:25,400
about what was being done in their name,

901
00:47:25,500 --> 00:47:28,032
they might help bring it to an end.

902
00:47:28,132 --> 00:47:31,865
He and Anthony Russo,
another RAND employee,

903
00:47:31,965 --> 00:47:35,365
secretly copied most of the report.

904
00:47:35,465 --> 00:47:39,565
Ellsberg offered it to three
leading antiwar senators,

905
00:47:39,666 --> 00:47:43,565
hoping they would be willing
to reveal its contents.

906
00:47:43,666 --> 00:47:46,300
None dared do it.

907
00:47:46,400 --> 00:47:49,900
Meanwhile, Neil Sheehan
of theNew York Times,

908
00:47:50,000 --> 00:47:54,032
who had been reporting
on Vietnam since 1962,

909
00:47:54,132 --> 00:47:57,900
and had already secretly
read some of the documents,

910
00:47:58,000 --> 00:48:01,965
asked Ellsberg to show
him the whole report.

911
00:48:02,065 --> 00:48:05,099
SHEEHAN: At that point, I was
very passionate about the war.

912
00:48:05,199 --> 00:48:08,632
I felt that it was really wrong,

913
00:48:08,733 --> 00:48:10,599
because we were getting a lot of Americans

914
00:48:10,699 --> 00:48:12,932
and a lot of Vietnamese
killed for no purpose.

915
00:48:13,032 --> 00:48:16,766
We were gonna lose this war.

916
00:48:16,865 --> 00:48:21,065
And so I vowed to myself
when I saw this material

917
00:48:21,166 --> 00:48:22,932
that this is never gonna go back

918
00:48:23,032 --> 00:48:24,599
into a government safe again.

919
00:48:24,699 --> 00:48:26,365
The American public had paid for it

920
00:48:26,465 --> 00:48:29,132
with the lives of their sons
and with their treasure,

921
00:48:29,233 --> 00:48:30,932
and it's gonna be published.

922
00:48:31,032 --> 00:48:32,599
NIXON: That piece in theTimes

923
00:48:32,699 --> 00:48:33,900
is, of course,

924
00:48:34,000 --> 00:48:37,065
a massive security leak from
the Pentagon, you know.

925
00:48:37,166 --> 00:48:38,865
ROGERS: Yeah.

926
00:48:38,965 --> 00:48:42,000
NIXON: It all relates, of course,
to everything up until we came in.

927
00:48:42,099 --> 00:48:43,699
ROGERS: Yeah.

928
00:48:43,800 --> 00:48:46,233
NIXON: And it's, uh, it's ver...
it's hard on Johnson,

929
00:48:46,333 --> 00:48:49,666
it's hard on Kennedy, it's hard on Lodge.

930
00:48:49,766 --> 00:48:53,166
NARRATOR: At first, Nixon
was not unduly disturbed

931
00:48:53,266 --> 00:48:55,666
by the newspaper's revelations.

932
00:48:55,766 --> 00:48:59,300
They reflected badly on his
Democratic predecessors,

933
00:48:59,400 --> 00:49:01,766
not on him.

934
00:49:01,865 --> 00:49:05,065
But Henry Kissinger quickly convinced Nixon

935
00:49:05,166 --> 00:49:06,965
that if theTime s were permitted

936
00:49:07,065 --> 00:49:10,800
to reveal the classified
secrets of earlier presidents,

937
00:49:10,900 --> 00:49:15,900
it was only a matter of time
until someone leaked his own.

938
00:49:16,000 --> 00:49:19,833
The Justice Department obtained
a temporary court order

939
00:49:19,932 --> 00:49:23,500
forbidding theTi mes from
publishing further installments

940
00:49:23,599 --> 00:49:26,632
on the grounds of national security.

941
00:49:26,733 --> 00:49:30,432
But soon, both theBoston Globe

942
00:49:30,532 --> 00:49:34,400
and theWashington Pos t were
also printing excerpts.

943
00:49:36,032 --> 00:49:38,565
On June 30, 1971,

944
00:49:38,666 --> 00:49:41,333
the United States Supreme Court,

945
00:49:41,432 --> 00:49:43,599
citing the First Amendment,

946
00:49:43,699 --> 00:49:47,266
ruled six to three that
theTimes had the right

947
00:49:47,365 --> 00:49:50,833
to publish the stolen documents.

948
00:49:50,932 --> 00:49:53,032
SHEEHAN: And I went down into the basement

949
00:49:53,132 --> 00:49:55,432
to wait for the presses to start to roll,

950
00:49:55,532 --> 00:49:58,132
and they had these huge
round reams of paper.

951
00:49:58,233 --> 00:49:59,333
(whirring)

952
00:49:59,432 --> 00:50:01,008
And, finally, the presses started to roll.

953
00:50:01,032 --> 00:50:05,465
And it was just an exquisite
moment of vindication

954
00:50:05,565 --> 00:50:07,699
of the freedom of the press in this country

955
00:50:07,800 --> 00:50:09,400
and how important it is.

956
00:50:09,500 --> 00:50:11,465
(rhythmic rattling)

957
00:50:11,565 --> 00:50:14,233
KARL MARLANTES: That changed

958
00:50:14,333 --> 00:50:16,233
our whole attitude toward government.

959
00:50:16,333 --> 00:50:18,699
Up until then, the president wouldn't lie.

960
00:50:18,800 --> 00:50:20,932
After then, they always lie.

961
00:50:21,032 --> 00:50:23,500
NARRATOR: The day the presses
began to roll again,

962
00:50:23,599 --> 00:50:26,833
Nixon ordered attorney
general John Mitchell

963
00:50:26,932 --> 00:50:30,500
to try to discredit Daniel
Ellsberg, who had just

964
00:50:30,599 --> 00:50:32,800
been indicted by a federal grand jury

965
00:50:32,900 --> 00:50:35,065
for theft and conspiracy

966
00:50:35,166 --> 00:50:39,132
under the Espionage Act of 1917.

967
00:51:14,099 --> 00:51:18,300
NARRATOR: Nixon feared Ellsberg
possessed more classified documents

968
00:51:18,400 --> 00:51:20,833
that would show that he himself had lied

969
00:51:20,932 --> 00:51:24,699
about the secret bombing
of Cambodia and Laos,

970
00:51:24,800 --> 00:51:27,532
and he believed that Ellsberg had had help

971
00:51:27,632 --> 00:51:31,065
and wanted to know the names
of his co-conspirators.

972
00:51:31,166 --> 00:51:33,500
The president created a private,

973
00:51:33,599 --> 00:51:36,900
clandestine investigative
unit within the White House.

974
00:51:37,000 --> 00:51:39,900
It came to be called "The Plumbers."

975
00:51:40,000 --> 00:51:43,532
John Ehrlichman, one of
Nixon's closest aides,

976
00:51:43,632 --> 00:51:47,000
eventually ordered them
to burglarize the office

977
00:51:47,099 --> 00:51:50,032
of Ellsberg's Los Angeles psychiatrist

978
00:51:50,132 --> 00:51:52,099
in search of material

979
00:51:52,199 --> 00:51:55,900
with which he could be
blackmailed into silence.

980
00:51:56,000 --> 00:52:00,199
Nixon may have privately
feared something else as well.

981
00:52:00,300 --> 00:52:03,099
He was told that the safe
at another think tank,

982
00:52:03,199 --> 00:52:06,800
the Brookings Institution
in Washington, D.C.,

983
00:52:06,900 --> 00:52:10,965
contained files that might
reveal the secret role

984
00:52:11,065 --> 00:52:14,932
his campaign had played in
torpedoing the peace talks

985
00:52:15,032 --> 00:52:18,233
on the eve of his election
three years earlier,

986
00:52:18,333 --> 00:52:22,932
which President Johnson had
then considered treason.

987
00:52:23,032 --> 00:52:26,733
Nixon wanted his "plumbers"
to break into Brookings,

988
00:52:26,833 --> 00:52:31,166
crack the safe, and remove the files.

989
00:52:31,266 --> 00:52:33,465
None of it was legal.

990
00:52:33,565 --> 00:52:36,699
Nixon did not care.

991
00:53:07,432 --> 00:53:11,666
NARRATOR: The Brookings break-in
would never take place.

992
00:53:11,766 --> 00:53:14,233
The burglars would be unable

993
00:53:14,333 --> 00:53:17,432
to find Ellsberg's file
in his doctor's office.

994
00:53:17,532 --> 00:53:20,965
But Nixon's obsession with his enemies

995
00:53:21,065 --> 00:53:24,800
would be the undoing of his presidency.

996
00:53:26,099 --> 00:53:29,565
("Embryonic Journey" by
Jefferson Airplane playing)

997
00:53:33,532 --> 00:53:35,500
(laughter and chatter)

998
00:53:42,065 --> 00:53:44,346
(indistinct voice of man
speaking French over microphone)

999
00:53:45,400 --> 00:53:47,666
JACK TODD: Once a month, I have a dream

1000
00:53:47,766 --> 00:53:52,300
that I'm... I'm back... I'm
back in basic training.

1001
00:53:52,400 --> 00:53:53,833
But I'm the age I am now,

1002
00:53:53,932 --> 00:53:56,199
which is way too old to be in the military.

1003
00:53:56,300 --> 00:53:58,666
But, you know, somehow
I've gotten a waiver,

1004
00:53:58,766 --> 00:54:00,365
and I'm going through all the training,

1005
00:54:00,465 --> 00:54:02,532
and there's some major war going on.

1006
00:54:02,632 --> 00:54:05,766
And I'm going to get there,
and I'm going to be a hero

1007
00:54:05,865 --> 00:54:11,166
and vindicate myself and be
taken back by my country.

1008
00:54:11,266 --> 00:54:13,099
(car horn honks)

1009
00:54:13,199 --> 00:54:17,432
NARRATOR: Jack Todd had crossed
into Canada in early 1970,

1010
00:54:17,532 --> 00:54:19,266
rather than take part

1011
00:54:19,365 --> 00:54:22,000
in what he believed to
be a dishonorable war.

1012
00:54:24,400 --> 00:54:28,166
He found himself living in a
strange underground world

1013
00:54:28,266 --> 00:54:30,333
of deserters and draft evaders

1014
00:54:30,432 --> 00:54:34,733
and the disaffected Canadians
who gathered around them.

1015
00:54:34,833 --> 00:54:38,900
In 1971, he was living in Montreal,

1016
00:54:39,000 --> 00:54:41,032
restless and often depressed,

1017
00:54:41,132 --> 00:54:44,733
increasingly alienated from his country,

1018
00:54:44,833 --> 00:54:47,965
but also anxious always for news from home,

1019
00:54:48,065 --> 00:54:50,833
and eager to know how his boyhood friends

1020
00:54:50,932 --> 00:54:53,965
from Scottsbluff, Nebraska, were doing.

1021
00:54:54,065 --> 00:54:56,666
One, named Ron Bales,

1022
00:54:56,766 --> 00:54:59,833
had lived just down the street.

1023
00:54:59,932 --> 00:55:04,699
And, uh... my mother sent me a letter, um,

1024
00:55:04,800 --> 00:55:06,965
and I remember taking
the clipping out of it.

1025
00:55:07,065 --> 00:55:10,565
I had walked up to Mount Royal
in Montreal to read the letter.

1026
00:55:10,666 --> 00:55:13,532
And the clipping was from
theScottsbluff Star-Herald,

1027
00:55:13,632 --> 00:55:16,400
and it was about Ron
being killed in Vietnam.

1028
00:55:19,632 --> 00:55:22,599
Why? Why?

1029
00:55:22,699 --> 00:55:26,666
It was long after we knew
how wrong the war was,

1030
00:55:26,766 --> 00:55:30,833
and guys like Ron were
still dying, you know.

1031
00:55:32,666 --> 00:55:34,599
Why?

1032
00:55:35,900 --> 00:55:38,233
The government today restricted the use

1033
00:55:38,333 --> 00:55:40,833
of the weed killer 2,4,5-T on the ground

1034
00:55:40,932 --> 00:55:42,833
that the chemical has caused birth defects

1035
00:55:42,932 --> 00:55:45,465
in some laboratory animals.

1036
00:55:47,365 --> 00:55:52,065
NARRATOR: Since 1962, American
and South Vietnamese forces

1037
00:55:52,166 --> 00:55:55,532
had sprayed some 20 million
gallons of herbicides

1038
00:55:55,632 --> 00:55:59,833
over roughly one quarter of South Vietnam.

1039
00:55:59,932 --> 00:56:03,099
The idea had been to reduce casualties

1040
00:56:03,199 --> 00:56:06,666
by clearing areas around U.S.
installations,

1041
00:56:06,766 --> 00:56:10,965
and to deny the enemy
crops and forest cover.

1042
00:56:11,065 --> 00:56:15,132
The most frequently used
defoliant was Agent Orange,

1043
00:56:15,233 --> 00:56:18,132
which contained 2,4,5-T.

1044
00:56:18,233 --> 00:56:20,300
When environmentalists convinced

1045
00:56:20,400 --> 00:56:23,465
the Nixon administration
to ban the weed killer

1046
00:56:23,565 --> 00:56:25,132
on American farms,

1047
00:56:25,233 --> 00:56:28,032
the Pentagon had reluctantly agreed

1048
00:56:28,132 --> 00:56:31,766
to stop using Agent Orange in Vietnam.

1049
00:56:31,865 --> 00:56:36,599
The ecological damage
defoliants did was obvious.

1050
00:56:36,699 --> 00:56:40,699
The damage done to soldiers and civilians

1051
00:56:40,800 --> 00:56:45,000
would be the subject of
angry debate for decades.

1052
00:56:48,300 --> 00:56:51,199
(crowd shouting in Vietnamese)

1053
00:56:51,300 --> 00:56:54,032
TED KOPPEL: Opposition
to the Saigon government

1054
00:56:54,132 --> 00:56:56,465
is not just Viet Cong.

1055
00:56:56,565 --> 00:56:58,065
TUE: How many governments

1056
00:56:58,166 --> 00:57:01,166
actually care for the Vietnamese people?

1057
00:57:01,266 --> 00:57:05,000
KOPPEL: The student antiwar,
anti-American movement

1058
00:57:05,099 --> 00:57:07,532
is larger than its small
demonstrations indicate.

1059
00:57:07,632 --> 00:57:10,400
TUE: You don't need military aid...

1060
00:57:12,465 --> 00:57:14,865
...to promote democracy in Vietnam.

1061
00:57:14,965 --> 00:57:18,233
To return to the Vietnamese people

1062
00:57:18,333 --> 00:57:20,666
their right that...

1063
00:57:20,766 --> 00:57:22,932
their right to speak freely.

1064
00:57:23,032 --> 00:57:25,699
You don't need even one penny.

1065
00:57:25,800 --> 00:57:28,900
You don't need to consult the White House,

1066
00:57:29,000 --> 00:57:31,932
you don't need to care
about the American media,

1067
00:57:32,032 --> 00:57:34,532
you don't need French,
you don't need Chinese,

1068
00:57:34,632 --> 00:57:36,199
you don't need Americans.

1069
00:57:36,300 --> 00:57:40,733
If you really care for Vietnam
then you turn back inside.

1070
00:57:40,833 --> 00:57:44,365
NARRATOR: South Vietnamese
president Nguyen Van Thieu

1071
00:57:44,465 --> 00:57:46,432
was campaigning for reelection.

1072
00:57:46,532 --> 00:57:48,865
The Americans had insisted on it

1073
00:57:48,965 --> 00:57:51,632
and urged him not to rig the race,

1074
00:57:51,733 --> 00:57:54,733
for fear it would resemble too closely

1075
00:57:54,833 --> 00:57:57,266
the fraudulent communist "elections"

1076
00:57:57,365 --> 00:58:00,766
routinely denounced by the United States.

1077
00:58:00,865 --> 00:58:02,432
But Thieu made sure

1078
00:58:02,532 --> 00:58:05,432
no serious candidates ran against him,

1079
00:58:05,532 --> 00:58:09,300
and claimed to have won 94% of the vote.

1080
00:58:09,400 --> 00:58:13,099
It became known as "the one-man election,"

1081
00:58:13,199 --> 00:58:14,365
and added to the ranks

1082
00:58:14,465 --> 00:58:17,465
of what was called the "Third Force":

1083
00:58:17,565 --> 00:58:21,333
South Vietnamese hoping for
a negotiated settlement

1084
00:58:21,432 --> 00:58:23,599
and an end to the bloodshed.

1085
00:58:40,333 --> 00:58:42,465
NARRATOR: By the middle of 1971,

1086
00:58:42,565 --> 00:58:45,465
Nixon and Kissinger were looking for a way

1087
00:58:45,565 --> 00:58:48,965
to get all U.S. troops out of Vietnam

1088
00:58:49,065 --> 00:58:51,565
before his re-election campaign began

1089
00:58:51,666 --> 00:58:53,565
the following year,

1090
00:58:53,666 --> 00:58:56,065
but to do so without causing

1091
00:58:56,166 --> 00:58:59,099
Saigon to fall too soon.

1092
00:59:35,900 --> 00:59:38,300
NARRATOR: At the secret talks in Paris,

1093
00:59:38,400 --> 00:59:41,465
Kissinger had offered his
North Vietnamese counterpart,

1094
00:59:41,565 --> 00:59:44,766
Le Duc Tho, the most
significant concessions

1095
00:59:44,865 --> 00:59:47,833
the United States had yet made:

1096
00:59:47,932 --> 00:59:51,432
North Vietnam could keep
its troops in the South...

1097
00:59:51,532 --> 00:59:53,432
tens of thousands of them.

1098
00:59:53,532 --> 00:59:57,932
And in exchange for the release
of American prisoners of war,

1099
00:59:58,032 --> 00:59:59,632
all American troops

1100
00:59:59,733 --> 01:00:03,000
would be withdrawn within seven months.

1101
01:00:05,199 --> 01:00:08,565
Le Duc Tho countered with
a new offer of his own:

1102
01:00:08,666 --> 01:00:10,865
Hanoi would release the prisoners

1103
01:00:10,965 --> 01:00:14,766
simultaneously with the
departure of U.S. forces.

1104
01:00:14,865 --> 01:00:18,032
But he still insisted
that Washington remove

1105
01:00:18,132 --> 01:00:21,599
President Thieu from power.

1106
01:00:21,699 --> 01:00:24,465
Kissinger was encouraged
that the North Vietnamese

1107
01:00:24,565 --> 01:00:28,333
seemed, for the first time,
to be negotiating seriously.

1108
01:00:28,432 --> 01:00:33,199
He could almost "taste
peace," he told a friend.

1109
01:00:33,300 --> 01:00:34,865
Thieu knew nothing

1110
01:00:34,965 --> 01:00:38,099
about the new American
concessions to Hanoi.

1111
01:00:38,199 --> 01:00:42,065
He was worried about something else.

1112
01:00:45,199 --> 01:00:47,199
ANNOUNCER: NBC News interrupts
regular programming

1113
01:00:47,233 --> 01:00:49,032
to bring you a special report.

1114
01:00:49,132 --> 01:00:51,599
The announcement I shall
now read is being issued

1115
01:00:51,699 --> 01:00:56,365
simultaneously in Peking
and in the United States.

1116
01:00:56,465 --> 01:00:58,132
NARRATOR: Richard Nixon,

1117
01:00:58,233 --> 01:01:01,333
famous for the ferocity
of his anticommunism,

1118
01:01:01,432 --> 01:01:03,965
astonished the world by announcing

1119
01:01:04,065 --> 01:01:07,599
that he was planning to
restore relations with China

1120
01:01:07,699 --> 01:01:11,065
that had been severed for
more than two decades.

1121
01:01:11,166 --> 01:01:14,800
The United States had
gone to war in Vietnam

1122
01:01:14,900 --> 01:01:17,932
in part to block Chinese expansionism.

1123
01:01:18,032 --> 01:01:22,166
What would Nixon's visit
mean for Thieu's future

1124
01:01:22,266 --> 01:01:24,500
or for that of his country?

1125
01:01:24,599 --> 01:01:27,766
Thieu was afraid he knew.

1126
01:01:27,865 --> 01:01:30,500
"America has been looking
for a new mistress,"

1127
01:01:30,599 --> 01:01:31,900
he told an aide,

1128
01:01:32,000 --> 01:01:34,733
"and now Nixon has discovered China.

1129
01:01:34,833 --> 01:01:38,565
"He does not want to have
the old mistress around.

1130
01:01:38,666 --> 01:01:42,400
Vietnam has become old and ugly."

1131
01:01:55,099 --> 01:01:58,699
KUSHNER: I believe it was
in the fall of 1971.

1132
01:02:01,300 --> 01:02:05,400
And they called us out and
they hung a bed sheet

1133
01:02:05,500 --> 01:02:10,166
and they had a projector and they showed us

1134
01:02:10,266 --> 01:02:13,733
color and black and white movies

1135
01:02:13,833 --> 01:02:17,132
of these protests in Washington.

1136
01:02:17,233 --> 01:02:19,166
(shouting)

1137
01:02:21,932 --> 01:02:23,865
And in the same film

1138
01:02:23,965 --> 01:02:26,132
it showed John Kerry.

1139
01:02:26,233 --> 01:02:28,365
And I remember he was very articulate,

1140
01:02:28,465 --> 01:02:30,632
very, very well spoken,

1141
01:02:30,733 --> 01:02:33,699
very fluent

1142
01:02:33,800 --> 01:02:36,400
and a good spokesman

1143
01:02:36,500 --> 01:02:37,900
for his cause.

1144
01:02:38,000 --> 01:02:40,065
Someone has to die so that President Nixon

1145
01:02:40,166 --> 01:02:42,766
won't be... and these are his words...

1146
01:02:42,865 --> 01:02:46,599
"the first president to lose a war."

1147
01:02:46,699 --> 01:02:47,865
And I remember very well,

1148
01:02:47,965 --> 01:02:50,500
he's sitting with his fatigue jacket

1149
01:02:50,599 --> 01:02:52,199
and long hair

1150
01:02:52,300 --> 01:02:54,432
and testifying about atrocities

1151
01:02:54,532 --> 01:02:56,465
and war crimes that...

1152
01:02:56,565 --> 01:02:58,565
we perpetrated.

1153
01:02:58,666 --> 01:03:01,632
Cut off limbs, blown up bodies,

1154
01:03:01,733 --> 01:03:04,000
randomly shot at civilians...

1155
01:03:04,099 --> 01:03:06,065
KUSHNER: But I was shocked by what he said.

1156
01:03:06,166 --> 01:03:07,900
And I didn't believe it.

1157
01:03:08,000 --> 01:03:11,365
I didn't believe it at all.

1158
01:03:13,099 --> 01:03:15,965
I mean, I'm sophisticated
to know, and I knew then,

1159
01:03:16,065 --> 01:03:18,565
that bad things happen in war
and they happen on both sides,

1160
01:03:18,666 --> 01:03:22,300
and I had seen the evidence
of the other side too, also.

1161
01:03:22,400 --> 01:03:23,699
And I knew it.

1162
01:03:23,800 --> 01:03:26,032
And... but still, to hear the testimony

1163
01:03:26,132 --> 01:03:31,065
and to hear it used as a weapon

1164
01:03:31,166 --> 01:03:33,699
against our further prosecution of this war

1165
01:03:33,800 --> 01:03:38,632
that we were suffering for
was very powerful indeed.

1166
01:03:38,733 --> 01:03:41,365
NARRATOR: A few months later

1167
01:03:41,465 --> 01:03:44,632
Kushner got an even bigger shock.

1168
01:03:44,733 --> 01:03:47,000
VALERIE KUSHNER (on recording):
My son has no father.

1169
01:03:47,099 --> 01:03:50,699
This Christmas Day we celebrate
the birth of a son to Mary

1170
01:03:50,800 --> 01:03:53,365
and this Christmas Day
some other mother's son

1171
01:03:53,465 --> 01:03:55,800
will die in Vietnam.

1172
01:03:55,900 --> 01:03:58,465
That death takes away all
that was taught to us

1173
01:03:58,565 --> 01:04:01,132
by Christ's birth.

1174
01:04:01,233 --> 01:04:03,532
KUSHNER: The whole time I was in the South

1175
01:04:03,632 --> 01:04:05,965
I never got one letter,
one bit of information.

1176
01:04:06,065 --> 01:04:08,099
When I got to North
Vietnam I got no letter,

1177
01:04:08,199 --> 01:04:10,632
no bit of information, nothing.

1178
01:04:10,733 --> 01:04:16,365
Then, I think it may have
been Christmas of '71,

1179
01:04:16,465 --> 01:04:20,900
my wife wrote an op-ed piece
in theNew York Times.

1180
01:04:21,000 --> 01:04:24,465
She had become politically active.

1181
01:04:24,565 --> 01:04:26,800
NARRATOR: The families of POWs

1182
01:04:26,900 --> 01:04:30,565
overwhelmingly supported
the Nixon administration.

1183
01:04:30,666 --> 01:04:33,565
Valerie Kushner did not,

1184
01:04:33,666 --> 01:04:35,300
and the North Vietnamese were quick

1185
01:04:35,400 --> 01:04:38,632
to exploit her antiwar views.

1186
01:04:38,733 --> 01:04:40,565
They broadcast a message

1187
01:04:40,666 --> 01:04:43,599
they had permitted her
husband to record for her.

1188
01:04:43,699 --> 01:04:46,400
It was the first time
she had heard his voice

1189
01:04:46,500 --> 01:04:48,432
in four years.

1190
01:04:50,766 --> 01:04:53,500
KUSHNER (on recording): I
received the glasses, Val,

1191
01:04:53,599 --> 01:04:56,365
and my eyes have improved considerably.

1192
01:04:56,465 --> 01:04:59,099
Please let me know about Brother John.

1193
01:04:59,199 --> 01:05:01,666
He or she is almost four now,

1194
01:05:01,766 --> 01:05:04,333
and he or she is old enough to understand

1195
01:05:04,432 --> 01:05:07,865
where Daddy is and that I love him or her

1196
01:05:07,965 --> 01:05:11,233
immeasurably despite our never meeting.

1197
01:05:11,333 --> 01:05:14,965
I calculate that T-Bird
is now in second grade,

1198
01:05:15,065 --> 01:05:17,099
and I know she is doing well.

1199
01:05:17,199 --> 01:05:19,000
She is a grown-up lady now

1200
01:05:19,099 --> 01:05:22,932
and I hope you have plans for
piano or ballet lessons soon.

1201
01:05:23,032 --> 01:05:25,532
Happy eighth birthday, dear T-Bird,

1202
01:05:25,632 --> 01:05:27,099
and Merry Christmas.

1203
01:05:27,199 --> 01:05:29,432
When I left you I promised to come home

1204
01:05:29,532 --> 01:05:31,065
before you were five.

1205
01:05:31,166 --> 01:05:34,900
I didn't fulfill that promise,
but when I do return,

1206
01:05:35,000 --> 01:05:37,565
I will never leave you again.

1207
01:05:37,666 --> 01:05:40,365
His optimism about the
whole situation amazes me.

1208
01:05:40,465 --> 01:05:41,833
I'm just very happy

1209
01:05:41,932 --> 01:05:44,300
that he can't see this morning's newspaper.

1210
01:05:44,400 --> 01:05:47,365
Because I-I don't have the same optimism

1211
01:05:47,465 --> 01:05:49,132
or the same confidence in this government

1212
01:05:49,233 --> 01:05:52,032
that he seems to have.

1213
01:05:56,000 --> 01:06:01,465
NARRATOR: President Nixon's visit
to China in February of 1972

1214
01:06:01,565 --> 01:06:04,099
not only alarmed President Thieu,

1215
01:06:04,199 --> 01:06:07,065
it worried Hanoi as well.

1216
01:06:07,166 --> 01:06:10,300
The North Vietnamese
remembered how Ho Chi Minh

1217
01:06:10,400 --> 01:06:13,300
had felt betrayed in 1954

1218
01:06:13,400 --> 01:06:16,000
when Moscow and Beijing had compelled them

1219
01:06:16,099 --> 01:06:20,233
to sign the Geneva Accords,
dividing Vietnam in two.

1220
01:06:20,333 --> 01:06:23,432
Now, they were concerned
that warmer relations

1221
01:06:23,532 --> 01:06:25,800
between the United States and China

1222
01:06:25,900 --> 01:06:29,699
might soon mean less support from Beijing.

1223
01:06:29,800 --> 01:06:33,632
Nixon was also planning to travel to Moscow

1224
01:06:33,733 --> 01:06:37,199
to meet with Soviet
premier Leonid Brezhnev,

1225
01:06:37,300 --> 01:06:39,099
seeking to ease tensions

1226
01:06:39,199 --> 01:06:43,000
with North Vietnam's
other communist patron.

1227
01:06:43,099 --> 01:06:47,800
Before that summit took place,
First Secretary Le Duan,

1228
01:06:47,900 --> 01:06:50,766
the man who headed the Politburo in Hanoi,

1229
01:06:50,865 --> 01:06:54,233
decided to undertake a
new kind of offensive.

1230
01:06:54,333 --> 01:06:58,032
It would be conventional warfare this time,

1231
01:06:58,132 --> 01:07:02,000
and on a scale he had
never before attempted.

1232
01:07:02,099 --> 01:07:04,900
Le Duan had several goals in mind:

1233
01:07:05,000 --> 01:07:07,333
to strengthen his hand at the peace talks

1234
01:07:07,432 --> 01:07:09,865
by altering the military balance of power

1235
01:07:09,965 --> 01:07:11,532
in South Vietnam,

1236
01:07:11,632 --> 01:07:15,032
to show that the ARVN could
not stand on their own,

1237
01:07:15,132 --> 01:07:18,833
and to convince the Soviets and the Chinese

1238
01:07:18,932 --> 01:07:22,800
his revolution was still worth supporting.

1239
01:07:26,932 --> 01:07:30,865
The assault began on March 30, 1972.

1240
01:07:30,965 --> 01:07:34,400
14 North Vietnamese infantry divisions...

1241
01:07:34,500 --> 01:07:37,132
more than 120,000 men...

1242
01:07:37,233 --> 01:07:39,733
now, for the first time,

1243
01:07:39,833 --> 01:07:43,766
supported by hundreds of
Soviet and Chinese-made tanks

1244
01:07:43,865 --> 01:07:48,932
and other armored vehicles,
attacked on three fronts:

1245
01:07:49,032 --> 01:07:52,699
across the demilitarized zone,

1246
01:07:52,800 --> 01:07:57,199
in the Central Highlands

1247
01:07:57,300 --> 01:08:01,766
and west of Saigon.

1248
01:08:01,865 --> 01:08:06,900
Americans would call it
"The Easter Offensive."

1249
01:08:07,000 --> 01:08:09,800
To the South Vietnamese,

1250
01:08:09,899 --> 01:08:13,432
it would be remembered as
"The Summer of Flames."

1251
01:08:13,533 --> 01:08:16,600
REPORTER: The South Vietnamese
Army knew this day was coming:

1252
01:08:16,699 --> 01:08:17,966
the day without Americans.

1253
01:08:18,065 --> 01:08:19,399
It was to be the big test,

1254
01:08:19,500 --> 01:08:20,733
both for them

1255
01:08:20,832 --> 01:08:23,765
and for President Nixon's
Vietnamization program.

1256
01:08:23,865 --> 01:08:26,733
The results in so far are not encouraging.

1257
01:08:26,832 --> 01:08:29,800
Whole battalions of the
government's third division

1258
01:08:29,899 --> 01:08:32,199
joined the refugees on the road south.

1259
01:08:32,300 --> 01:08:36,132
They had been outnumbered,
overpowered, overwhelmed.

1260
01:08:36,233 --> 01:08:38,432
NARRATOR: An entire ARVN regiment

1261
01:08:38,533 --> 01:08:40,733
surrendered at Camp Carroll.

1262
01:08:40,832 --> 01:08:42,600
North Vietnamese troops

1263
01:08:42,699 --> 01:08:45,500
then swiftly overran Quang Tri Province,

1264
01:08:45,600 --> 01:08:50,565
driving tens of thousands of
terrified refugees southward.

1265
01:08:50,666 --> 01:08:54,199
They nearly cut South Vietnam in half

1266
01:08:54,300 --> 01:08:57,033
through the Central Highlands

1267
01:08:57,132 --> 01:09:01,332
and drove toward Saigon,
hoping to seize large areas

1268
01:09:01,432 --> 01:09:04,365
along the Cambodian border.

1269
01:09:04,466 --> 01:09:07,265
It looked as if it were going to be

1270
01:09:07,365 --> 01:09:10,033
a total defeat for the ARVN.

1271
01:09:10,132 --> 01:09:14,065
There were only 60,000 U.S.
military personnel

1272
01:09:14,166 --> 01:09:16,132
left in South Vietnam,

1273
01:09:16,233 --> 01:09:19,233
and very few of them were combat troops.

1274
01:09:21,765 --> 01:09:24,865
Suddenly, the survival of
everything Nixon and Kissinger

1275
01:09:24,966 --> 01:09:27,199
had worked for was in peril.

1276
01:09:27,300 --> 01:09:31,632
They had to do something... and fast.

1277
01:09:53,800 --> 01:09:57,233
NARRATOR: Nixon ordered
up Operation Linebacker...

1278
01:09:57,332 --> 01:09:59,832
massive air attacks

1279
01:09:59,932 --> 01:10:01,332
on the advancing North Vietnamese.

1280
01:10:03,132 --> 01:10:05,233
"The bastards have never been bombed

1281
01:10:05,332 --> 01:10:08,265
"like they're going to
be this time," he said.

1282
01:10:11,966 --> 01:10:15,166
The most crucial battle
of the Easter Offensive

1283
01:10:15,265 --> 01:10:17,000
was fought at An Loc,

1284
01:10:17,100 --> 01:10:19,666
a city that commanded Route 13,

1285
01:10:19,765 --> 01:10:23,000
a paved highway that led
directly to Saigon,

1286
01:10:23,100 --> 01:10:25,399
just 60 miles away.

1287
01:10:28,265 --> 01:10:30,600
North Vietnamese artillery fire

1288
01:10:30,699 --> 01:10:32,632
and a massive infantry and armor attack

1289
01:10:32,733 --> 01:10:34,832
drove the city's ARVN defenders

1290
01:10:34,932 --> 01:10:39,233
into an area less than a mile square.

1291
01:10:39,332 --> 01:10:44,666
Repeated efforts to reinforce
and resupply them failed.

1292
01:10:44,765 --> 01:10:48,065
The ARVN bravely held out.

1293
01:10:48,166 --> 01:10:50,600
JAMES WILLBANKS: The
number one thing we did

1294
01:10:50,699 --> 01:10:53,300
was coordinate the air strikes.

1295
01:10:53,399 --> 01:10:55,832
General Hollingsworth
went to General Abrams

1296
01:10:55,932 --> 01:10:58,033
and begged for all the B-52s he could get,

1297
01:10:58,132 --> 01:10:59,966
and on the 10th and 11th of May,

1298
01:11:00,065 --> 01:11:05,765
he planned a B-52 strike every
50 minutes for 24 hours.

1299
01:11:16,432 --> 01:11:17,666
NARRATOR: In the end,

1300
01:11:17,765 --> 01:11:22,166
American airpower made the difference.

1301
01:11:27,699 --> 01:11:30,365
The North Vietnamese and
their armored columns,

1302
01:11:30,466 --> 01:11:31,899
massed in the open,

1303
01:11:32,000 --> 01:11:35,832
proved easy targets for American pilots.

1304
01:11:35,932 --> 01:11:39,899
"This," one American advisor said,

1305
01:11:40,000 --> 01:11:43,966
"was the kind of war we came to fight."

1306
01:11:54,632 --> 01:11:57,600
PHAM LUC:

1307
01:12:35,865 --> 01:12:37,600
(explosion)

1308
01:12:37,699 --> 01:12:41,000
NARRATOR: The North Vietnamese
suffered 10,000 casualties

1309
01:12:41,100 --> 01:12:42,832
at An Loc alone

1310
01:12:42,932 --> 01:12:47,065
and lost most of their
tanks and heavy artillery.

1311
01:12:47,166 --> 01:12:48,666
(explosions continue)

1312
01:12:50,466 --> 01:12:52,899
WILLBANKS: The bottom line
was that all the air power

1313
01:12:53,000 --> 01:12:54,600
in the world would not make a difference

1314
01:12:54,699 --> 01:12:56,108
if the ARVN hadn't stood and fought.

1315
01:12:56,132 --> 01:12:57,565
(people shouting)

1316
01:12:57,666 --> 01:13:01,033
They had held Kon Tum,
they had held An Loc,

1317
01:13:01,132 --> 01:13:02,800
they had re-taken Quang Tri.

1318
01:13:02,899 --> 01:13:04,966
They had taken the best
that the North Vietnamese

1319
01:13:05,065 --> 01:13:06,699
had to throw at them.

1320
01:13:06,800 --> 01:13:10,033
So I thought if we continue
to maintain that support,

1321
01:13:10,132 --> 01:13:11,332
perhaps they had a chance.

1322
01:13:11,432 --> 01:13:15,332
DUONG VAN MAI ELLIOTT: The
Easter Offensive, to me,

1323
01:13:15,432 --> 01:13:18,666
showed that the South
Vietnamese could fight,

1324
01:13:18,765 --> 01:13:21,733
but only up to a certain point.

1325
01:13:21,832 --> 01:13:24,500
So, my question would be,

1326
01:13:24,600 --> 01:13:26,500
what would happen when the Americans left

1327
01:13:26,600 --> 01:13:29,166
with their B-52s, you know?

1328
01:13:29,265 --> 01:13:30,765
(protestors chanting)

1329
01:13:30,865 --> 01:13:33,932
NARRATOR: Americans may have
approved of the renewed use

1330
01:13:34,033 --> 01:13:37,300
of American air power to
stop the communist advance

1331
01:13:37,399 --> 01:13:38,765
into the South,

1332
01:13:38,865 --> 01:13:43,432
but Nixon had also ordered
American planes to resume

1333
01:13:43,533 --> 01:13:46,733
sustained bombing of North Vietnam,

1334
01:13:46,832 --> 01:13:50,399
which had been halted since
the Johnson administration.

1335
01:13:50,500 --> 01:13:54,300
Some saw the new bombing,
which vastly exceeded

1336
01:13:54,399 --> 01:13:56,399
all previous campaigns,

1337
01:13:56,500 --> 01:14:01,233
as evidence that a war Nixon
had promised was winding down

1338
01:14:01,332 --> 01:14:04,100
was once again being escalated.

1339
01:14:04,199 --> 01:14:07,533
(plane soaring)

1340
01:14:07,632 --> 01:14:09,065
LESLIE GELB: The bombing campaign

1341
01:14:09,166 --> 01:14:10,632
was much more extensive

1342
01:14:10,733 --> 01:14:15,199
than the bombing campaign
under Lyndon Johnson.

1343
01:14:15,300 --> 01:14:16,365
And from a standpoint

1344
01:14:16,466 --> 01:14:18,966
of pressuring them to make concessions

1345
01:14:19,065 --> 01:14:20,899
at the negotiating table,

1346
01:14:21,000 --> 01:14:23,365
historically, that's how you did it.

1347
01:14:23,466 --> 01:14:25,699
Only it didn't work with these guys.

1348
01:14:25,800 --> 01:14:27,632
(bombs exploding)

1349
01:14:27,733 --> 01:14:29,399
They took the pounding.

1350
01:14:31,466 --> 01:14:33,265
(men yelling in Vietnamese)

1351
01:14:36,533 --> 01:14:40,132
NARRATOR: Le Minh Khue,
who had served four years

1352
01:14:40,233 --> 01:14:43,600
as a Youth Volunteer on
the Ho Chi Minh trail,

1353
01:14:43,699 --> 01:14:46,332
was now back home in North Vietnam.

1354
01:14:47,632 --> 01:14:50,832
LE MINH KHUE:

1355
01:15:28,399 --> 01:15:31,300
NARRATOR: Among the thousands
of South Vietnamese

1356
01:15:31,399 --> 01:15:34,100
who lost their lives in
the Easter Offensive

1357
01:15:34,199 --> 01:15:37,365
was the brother of Phan Quang Tue.

1358
01:15:37,466 --> 01:15:40,000
PHAN QUANG TUE: I had a brother, Tuan.

1359
01:15:40,100 --> 01:15:44,199
And we were raised together.

1360
01:15:44,300 --> 01:15:48,000
He would have been now 67.

1361
01:15:48,100 --> 01:15:50,832
When his plane was shot down

1362
01:15:50,932 --> 01:15:55,000
and later on they weren't
able to recover him,

1363
01:15:55,100 --> 01:15:57,666
his body, so he disappeared,

1364
01:15:57,765 --> 01:16:02,132
he was missing in action,
he was 26 years old.

1365
01:16:02,233 --> 01:16:05,600
He has his full life ahead of him.

1366
01:16:05,699 --> 01:16:08,699
(voice breaking): Tuan never
had a chance to live his life.

1367
01:16:10,800 --> 01:16:14,432
And I can never overcome the feeling,

1368
01:16:14,533 --> 01:16:18,632
as to himself

1369
01:16:18,733 --> 01:16:20,966
and his generation,

1370
01:16:21,065 --> 01:16:24,300
sacrifice their lives for what?

1371
01:16:26,132 --> 01:16:30,466
And the frustrating thing is
that even Vietnamese themself

1372
01:16:30,565 --> 01:16:32,500
do not seem to value that loss.

1373
01:16:38,800 --> 01:16:41,800
NIXON: There's only one
way to stop the killing.

1374
01:16:41,899 --> 01:16:45,533
That is to keep the weapons
of war out of the hands

1375
01:16:45,632 --> 01:16:51,365
of the international
outlaws of North Vietnam.

1376
01:16:51,466 --> 01:16:52,699
Throughout the war in Vietnam,

1377
01:16:52,800 --> 01:16:55,565
the United States has exercised
a degree of restraint

1378
01:16:55,666 --> 01:16:57,800
unprecedented in the annals of war...

1379
01:16:57,899 --> 01:16:59,399
(planes flying overhead)

1380
01:16:59,500 --> 01:17:02,300
NARRATOR: Le Duan's Easter
Offensive, like Tet,

1381
01:17:02,399 --> 01:17:04,632
had been a great gamble.

1382
01:17:04,733 --> 01:17:07,466
So was Nixon's next move.

1383
01:17:07,565 --> 01:17:10,600
The massive North Vietnamese
assault had failed,

1384
01:17:10,699 --> 01:17:12,100
the president said,

1385
01:17:12,199 --> 01:17:15,233
but it could never have been
mounted in the first place

1386
01:17:15,332 --> 01:17:17,832
without weapons and
supplies provided by China

1387
01:17:17,932 --> 01:17:20,500
and the Soviet Union.

1388
01:17:20,600 --> 01:17:24,765
Accordingly, he ordered 11,000 mines laid

1389
01:17:24,865 --> 01:17:28,265
in North Vietnamese waters
to block further access

1390
01:17:28,365 --> 01:17:30,033
to Haiphong harbor.

1391
01:17:30,132 --> 01:17:33,865
It was something the Joint
Chiefs had been asking for

1392
01:17:33,966 --> 01:17:35,800
for years.

1393
01:17:35,899 --> 01:17:38,033
The scheduled summit with the Soviets

1394
01:17:38,132 --> 01:17:39,832
was just two weeks away,

1395
01:17:39,932 --> 01:17:42,132
and some advisors had urged the president

1396
01:17:42,233 --> 01:17:45,166
not to take any action
that directly threatened

1397
01:17:45,265 --> 01:17:49,033
Soviet ships, for fear
they would cancel it.

1398
01:17:49,132 --> 01:17:51,733
Nixon thought he had to take the risk.

1399
01:17:51,832 --> 01:17:55,899
And so he spoke directly to Moscow.

1400
01:17:56,000 --> 01:17:59,432
Let us not slide back
toward the dark shadows

1401
01:17:59,533 --> 01:18:02,365
of a previous age.

1402
01:18:02,466 --> 01:18:07,132
We do not ask you to
sacrifice your principles

1403
01:18:07,233 --> 01:18:09,233
or your friends,

1404
01:18:09,332 --> 01:18:12,666
but neither should you
permit Hanoi's intransigence

1405
01:18:12,765 --> 01:18:15,365
to blot out the prospects we together

1406
01:18:15,466 --> 01:18:16,832
have so patiently prepared.

1407
01:18:19,666 --> 01:18:22,399
NARRATOR: Nixon's gamble paid off.

1408
01:18:22,500 --> 01:18:24,065
The Soviets and the Chinese denounced

1409
01:18:24,166 --> 01:18:29,600
the president's action,
but then did nothing.

1410
01:18:29,699 --> 01:18:34,765
On May 26, the United States
and the Soviet Union signed

1411
01:18:34,865 --> 01:18:38,800
an historic Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty,

1412
01:18:38,899 --> 01:18:42,100
the first agreement to
limit nuclear armaments

1413
01:18:42,199 --> 01:18:44,565
since the Cold War began.

1414
01:18:44,666 --> 01:18:47,733
For the Soviet Union, for China,

1415
01:18:47,832 --> 01:18:50,199
as well as for the United States,

1416
01:18:50,300 --> 01:18:54,800
Vietnam's significance
was steadily receding.

1417
01:19:31,399 --> 01:19:33,166
NIXON: I know.

1418
01:19:57,065 --> 01:19:59,000
(camera shutter clicks)

1419
01:20:01,199 --> 01:20:05,765
NARRATOR: On the morning of June 8, 1972,

1420
01:20:05,865 --> 01:20:10,265
Nick Ut, a 21-year-old South
Vietnamese photographer

1421
01:20:10,365 --> 01:20:12,600
working for the Associated Press,

1422
01:20:12,699 --> 01:20:16,132
was accompanying ARVN
troops on Highway One,

1423
01:20:16,233 --> 01:20:18,699
moving toward a village called Trang Bang,

1424
01:20:18,800 --> 01:20:21,565
to dislodge North Vietnamese forces

1425
01:20:21,666 --> 01:20:25,432
that had occupied it during
the Easter Offensive.

1426
01:20:25,533 --> 01:20:28,699
Ut was beginning to put his cameras away,

1427
01:20:28,800 --> 01:20:30,733
ready to return to Saigon,

1428
01:20:30,832 --> 01:20:35,565
when he saw a South Vietnamese
fighter suddenly dip down

1429
01:20:35,666 --> 01:20:37,699
toward the fleeing refugees,

1430
01:20:37,800 --> 01:20:40,699
whom the pilot mistook for the enemy.

1431
01:20:40,800 --> 01:20:45,033
(explosions)

1432
01:20:45,132 --> 01:20:49,932
(camera shutter clicking)

1433
01:20:54,166 --> 01:20:57,399
(speaking English):

1434
01:21:31,600 --> 01:21:33,132
(speaking Vietnamese)

1435
01:22:04,166 --> 01:22:09,199
NARRATOR: Ut drove the badly
burned girl, Kim Phuc,

1436
01:22:09,300 --> 01:22:11,533
and several other injured children

1437
01:22:11,632 --> 01:22:13,865
to a hospital in Saigon.

1438
01:22:13,966 --> 01:22:18,332
She had been burned over 30% of her body.

1439
01:22:18,432 --> 01:22:21,666
Then, Ut raced to the AP darkroom

1440
01:22:21,765 --> 01:22:25,166
to find out what he had caught on film.

1441
01:22:43,399 --> 01:22:46,265
NARRATOR: His photo
editor in Saigon told him

1442
01:22:46,365 --> 01:22:49,332
they could not send the
picture out on the wire,

1443
01:22:49,432 --> 01:22:51,800
because the girl was naked.

1444
01:22:51,899 --> 01:22:54,332
But then Ut's boss,

1445
01:22:54,432 --> 01:22:58,100
the legendary combat
photographer Horst Faas,

1446
01:22:58,199 --> 01:23:00,132
saw the pictures.

1447
01:23:00,600 --> 01:23:02,265
UT:

1448
01:23:12,065 --> 01:23:15,966
NARRATOR: Nick Ut's photograph appeared

1449
01:23:16,065 --> 01:23:18,865
on front pages around the world

1450
01:23:18,966 --> 01:23:22,899
and won the Pulitzer Prize.

1451
01:23:23,000 --> 01:23:25,899
For many Americans,

1452
01:23:26,000 --> 01:23:29,233
even many of those who
had supported the war,

1453
01:23:29,332 --> 01:23:33,932
the image seemed to signal
that enough was enough.

1454
01:23:37,533 --> 01:23:39,899
Kim Phuc would survive.

1455
01:23:40,000 --> 01:23:45,432
She eventually left Vietnam
and settled outside Toronto.

1456
01:23:50,899 --> 01:23:55,100
(cheers and applause)

1457
01:23:55,199 --> 01:23:57,265
(rhythmic clapping)

1458
01:24:00,865 --> 01:24:04,865
I introduce Valerie Kushner of Virginia

1459
01:24:04,966 --> 01:24:07,632
to second the nomination
of George McGovern.

1460
01:24:07,733 --> 01:24:09,932
(applause and cheering)

1461
01:24:10,033 --> 01:24:13,632
Mr. Chairman, Democrats,

1462
01:24:13,733 --> 01:24:18,199
my participation in this
convention is a tribute

1463
01:24:18,300 --> 01:24:21,466
to the reforms instituted
by the Democratic Party,

1464
01:24:21,565 --> 01:24:25,500
for I am a woman, and I am under 30.

1465
01:24:25,600 --> 01:24:29,166
But I also represent an
even smaller minority:

1466
01:24:29,265 --> 01:24:32,000
the wives of Americans who are missing

1467
01:24:32,100 --> 01:24:34,533
or imprisoned in Southeast Asia.

1468
01:24:34,632 --> 01:24:38,166
(cheers and applause)

1469
01:24:38,265 --> 01:24:40,932
NARRATOR: Valerie Kushner,

1470
01:24:41,033 --> 01:24:44,500
hoping to get her husband,
Hal, home as soon as possible,

1471
01:24:44,600 --> 01:24:47,533
had become an ardent
supporter of the candidacy

1472
01:24:47,632 --> 01:24:51,233
of Senator George McGovern of South Dakota.

1473
01:24:51,332 --> 01:24:55,365
A decorated bomber pilot in World War II,

1474
01:24:55,466 --> 01:24:58,166
McGovern had called for an early end

1475
01:24:58,265 --> 01:24:59,565
to the bombing of the North,

1476
01:24:59,666 --> 01:25:02,765
a halt to Congressional
funding for the war,

1477
01:25:02,865 --> 01:25:04,765
and immediate withdrawal

1478
01:25:04,865 --> 01:25:09,432
from Vietnam once the POWs were released.

1479
01:25:09,533 --> 01:25:12,932
I knew that he would bring my husband home.

1480
01:25:13,033 --> 01:25:15,666
(applause)

1481
01:25:17,199 --> 01:25:21,865
But even more important, he
will bring America home.

1482
01:25:21,966 --> 01:25:24,932
(applause and cheering)

1483
01:25:25,033 --> 01:25:28,033
And it is for that reason

1484
01:25:28,132 --> 01:25:30,399
that I am proud to second the nomination

1485
01:25:30,500 --> 01:25:35,233
of our next president, Senator George S.
McGovern.

1486
01:25:35,332 --> 01:25:38,265
(applause and cheering)

1487
01:25:40,800 --> 01:25:43,033
NARRATOR: By the time her candidate

1488
01:25:43,132 --> 01:25:45,533
finally accepted the nomination,

1489
01:25:45,632 --> 01:25:48,265
it was 2:48 in the morning.

1490
01:25:48,365 --> 01:25:51,300
Most Americans were asleep.

1491
01:25:51,399 --> 01:25:56,233
McGOVERN: During four
administrations of both parties,

1492
01:25:56,332 --> 01:26:01,300
a terrible war has been
charted behind closed doors.

1493
01:26:01,399 --> 01:26:03,432
(cheers and applause)

1494
01:26:03,533 --> 01:26:05,899
I want those doors opened,

1495
01:26:06,000 --> 01:26:09,000
and I want that war closed.

1496
01:26:09,100 --> 01:26:11,765
(raucous cheers and applause)

1497
01:26:11,865 --> 01:26:13,332
(static)

1498
01:26:13,432 --> 01:26:17,132
NARRATOR: McGovern's
campaign quickly collapsed.

1499
01:26:17,233 --> 01:26:20,432
He botched the selection
of his running mate,

1500
01:26:20,533 --> 01:26:23,800
and secretly asked an aide in Paris

1501
01:26:23,899 --> 01:26:27,166
to talk with the North
Vietnamese about POWs,

1502
01:26:27,265 --> 01:26:32,365
and then denied he'd meddled
in the peace process.

1503
01:26:32,466 --> 01:26:34,432
Organized labor,

1504
01:26:34,533 --> 01:26:37,600
traditionally the Democrats'
most reliable ally,

1505
01:26:37,699 --> 01:26:40,533
refused to endorse the party's candidate

1506
01:26:40,632 --> 01:26:44,166
for the first time in 20 years.

1507
01:26:44,265 --> 01:26:50,000
McGovern's poll numbers eroded
steadily over the summer.

1508
01:26:50,100 --> 01:26:53,033
Still, hoping to find material

1509
01:26:53,132 --> 01:26:56,033
that might be used to smear the opposition,

1510
01:26:56,132 --> 01:26:59,765
Nixon's aides had already
authorized the Plumbers

1511
01:26:59,865 --> 01:27:02,065
to make another break-in,

1512
01:27:02,166 --> 01:27:05,800
this time at Democratic
National Headquarters

1513
01:27:05,899 --> 01:27:08,699
in the Washington, D.C., apartment complex

1514
01:27:08,800 --> 01:27:11,733
called the Watergate.

1515
01:27:11,832 --> 01:27:13,832
They had been caught.

1516
01:27:13,932 --> 01:27:16,565
JOHN CHANCELLOR: One of the most
fascinating and exotic stories

1517
01:27:16,666 --> 01:27:18,365
ever to come out of Washington, D.C.,

1518
01:27:18,466 --> 01:27:20,399
is the talk of the Capitol today.

1519
01:27:20,500 --> 01:27:22,466
Five men were arrested early Saturday

1520
01:27:22,565 --> 01:27:25,365
while trying to install
eavesdropping equipment

1521
01:27:25,466 --> 01:27:27,565
at the Democratic National Committee.

1522
01:27:27,666 --> 01:27:29,865
And it turns out that one
of them has an office

1523
01:27:29,966 --> 01:27:32,233
in the headquarters of the Committee

1524
01:27:32,332 --> 01:27:34,065
for the Re-Election of the President.

